definition.value: Sexual intercourse in which some anatomical structure is stimulated by the hand without penetration.
Stimulation of genitals by two or more people who stimulate themselves or one another. Such acts may be penetrative, non-penetrative, or both.
Modification of the execution of an event or a process.
A pattern in which a group or groups of organisms are structured in relation to sexual behavior.
A gathering of individuals who meet at an arranged place and time in order to discuss or engage in some common interest.
Any of various sexual attractions considered nonnormative.

Disorders that include recurrent, intense sexually arousing fantasies, sexual urges, or behaviors generally involving nonhuman objects, suffering of oneself or partners, or children or other nonconsenting partners.

The American Psychiatric Association notes that most atypical sexual interests, while possibly considered paraphilic, do not constitute a mental health problem and thus are not considered paraphilic disorders. For example, in a paraphilic disorder, the psychological distress one feels about their paraphilic desire must be distinct from the general societal or cultural disapproval of such a desire.

A fetishistic disorder is an extreme sexual attraction to non-human objects or body parts which are not traditionally considered sexual which occurs alongside distress or impairment deemed clinically significant.

Because the word "fetish" is used in so many contexts, it can be difficult to determine what constitutes a fetishistic disorder. For example, fetishization of feminine breasts is relatively common and would only be considered a fetishistic disorder under extreme circumstances.
Sexual attraction to children by adults.
Sexual behavior involving young adolescents or children in a sense that is nonnormative and typically criminal in the given society, such as child rape in the contemporary United States.
Undertaking or practicing the dominant role in BDSM activities.

Traditionally, a sexual fixation on a nonliving object or nongenital body part. However, the term has been extended in common discourse to mean any sexual behavior pattern wherein an "abnormal" degree of gratification is linked to a particular object, activity, quality, etc.
A pronounced sexual interest in feet.
A form of sexual roleplaying in which an individual acts or treats another as if they were a different age.

A term usually used to refer to a castrated person assigned male at birth (depending on the exact person they may or may not have had a male gender identity). Notably though, some sources simply used the term to refer to palace officials who may or may not have been castrated males. Alternatively used to refer to modern persons who identify as eunuchs.

In modern language, this term should be avoided whenever possible because it is unclear what is being referred to and can be construed as offensive under certain circumstances. However, the term can be appropriately applied in historical contexts.
A pale purple color, like that of the lavender flower. Lavender become symbol of homosexuality in the 1950s and 1960s, just as the color mauve was in the 1890s.
A significant pattern of gender dysphoria or other incongruence between one's gender identity and one's sexual characteristics.
Sexually attracted to people regardless of gender; alternatively, sexually attracted to people of all genders or any gender.

A cultural gender role in some Chumash communities involving persons who may be considered to be assigned male at birth. Henry notes that ag has been "ranslated as homosexual, transvestite, and third gender None of these concepts quite captures the social and mystical importance of the [ag], however".
A Yup'ik person who is part of a certain non-binary cultural gender role in those communities and who may, in modern times, be assigned female at birth.
A Yup'ik person who is part of a certain non-binary cultural gender role in those communities and who may, in modern times, be assigned male at birth.

A cultural practice in parts of Afghanistan and Pakistan, in which some families without sons will pick a daughter to live and behave as a boy. This enables the child to behave more freely: attending school, escorting her sisters in public, and working. Bacha posh also allows the family to avoid the social stigma associated of not having any male children.
Sexual behavior involving young adolescents or children in a sense that may be normative in the given society, such as pederasty was in ancient Greece.

A slang term in Afghanistan for a wide variety of activities involving sexual relations between older men and younger adolescent men, or boys. The practitioner is commonly called bacha baz (meaning "boy play" in Dari) or simply bach. It may include to some extent sexual slavery and child prostitution. Bacha bz is currently reported in various parts of Afghanistan. Force and coercion are common, and security officials state they are unable to end such practices because many of the men involved in bacha bazi-related activities are powerful and well-armed warlords.

Gender variance, or, sometimes, gender nonconformity, is behavior or gender expression exhibited by an individual that does not match cultural/social masculine and feminine gender norms and/or expectations.

"Gender non-conforming" and "gender diverse" are often preferred to "gender variant" because "gender variant" (and, by extension, "gender variance") implies a standard normative for gender (i.e. a way gender is "supposed to be"). However, many resources emply the term as a helpful "catch-all" for various transgender and cultural gender roles and identities.

A gender role observed in many communities on the Indian subcontinent. Many hijras also consider themselves to be transgender women or intersex persons, but the concept predates that terminology. Hijra are almost exclusively assigned male at birth and some undergo an initiation ritual called nirwaan (nirvan), which involves removal of the penis, scrotum, and testicles.
The term "hijra" is sometimes considered offensive in Pakistan, with the Urdu   (khwaja sara) being preferred.

Note that hijra who might "fit" the designation of transgender woman may not identify as such, and will thus not be filed under both designations. Further, not all Indian, Pakistani, and Bengali transgender women are hijra, and thus will not be included in this categorization.
The word hijra has historically been translated into English as "eunuch" or "hermaphrodite" but this contextualization is both inappropriate and inaccurate.

Hijras tend to reside in somewhat intentional communities, being ostensibly separate from other Indian gender and sexual minorities. They engage in specific rituals and professions and utilize an argot known as Hijra Farsi, which is a blend of Persian and Hindustani.

A heterogeneous gender role or categorization of the Indian subcontinent. Typically used to refer to persons assigned male at birth who take on a passive role in sexual relationships with other men (analogous to the idea of a "bottom" in many English-speaking countries).
Kothi differ significantly from hijra in that the former do not live in intentional communities as hijra often do. However, some hijra identify as kothi and vice versa.
Note that some kothi identify as bisexual or pansexual, not necessarily as exclusively gay.
Transgender identity in Japan which is not considered male or female. Sometimes considered equivalent to words like genderqueer or non-binary.
Individuals who are X-gender may refer to themselves as FTX (female to X-gender) or MTX (male to X-gender) instead of FTM or MTF.
A grammatical gender which is feminine.
A grammatical gender which is masculine.
A word that is used with a noun (as a standalone word or a prefix or suffix) to specify grammatical definiteness of the noun, and in some languages extending to volume or numerical scope.

The belief in the superiority of one race over another. It may also include prejudice, discrimination, or antagonism directed against other people because they are of a different race or ethnicity, or the belief that members of different races or ethnicities should be treated differently.
A form of prejudice or discrimination usually from members of the same race in which people are treated differently based on the social implications from cultural meanings attached to skin color.
Fear of sex or negative attitudes about sex (sex as in sexuality and/or sexual intercourse).
Rape involving at least two or more violators (typically at least three).

Camp can also be a social practice and function as a style and performance identity for several types of entertainment including film, cabaret, and pantomime. Where high art necessarily incorporates beauty and value, camp necessarily needs to be lively, audacious and dynamic.

An aesthetic style and sensibility that regards something as appealing because of its bad taste and ironic value. Camp aesthetics disrupt many of modernism's notions of what art is and what can be classified as high art by inverting aesthetic attributes such as beauty, value, and taste through an invitation of a different kind of apprehension and consumption.

The gay panic defense is a legal defense, usually against charges of assault or murder. A defendant using the defense claims they acted in a state of violent temporary insanity because of unwanted homosexual advances from another individual. The defendant alleges to find the same-sex sexual advances so offensive and frightening that it brings on a psychotic state characterized by unusual violence.
The act of dominating; exercise of power in ruling; dominion; supremacy; authority, often when arbitrary or insolent.

Persons, usually in the United States, who identify as Latine; broadly, all Latin American persons. In this context, persons from countries and dependencies in the Western Hemisphere where Romance languages such as Spanish, Portuguese, and French are predominantly spoken; it is broader than the terms Iberian or Hispanic.

Reactions to Latinx as a neologism have been mixed, with the most criticism coming from native Spanish speakers. There tends to be a generational and regional divide among supporters and critics of the term, with more support among young people in the United States, and more criticism among older generations, and from those outside the United States. Similar words used for this purpose include Chicanx, Latin@ and Latine. A 2019 poll found that 2% of Americans of Latin American descent preferred to use 'Latinx', and 3% of 18-34 year olds. Latine has since become the more preferred term, as it has more of a linguistic basis in Spanish than "Latinx" or "Latin@".

The other human being in their differences from the self, as being a cumulative, constituting factor in the self-image of a person; as acknowledgement of being real. Usually, the "other" is used in relationship to the quality of "otherness", he state of being different from and alien to the social identity of a person and to the identity of the self. To "other" someone (as a verb) is to reduce them by labeling and defining them as a subaltern native, as someone who belongs to the socially subordinate category of the other.

A pale tint of red that is named after a flower of the same name. It was first used as a color name in the late 17th century. According to surveys in Europe and the United States, pink is the color most often associated with charm, politeness, sensitivity, tenderness, sweetness, childhood, femininity and romance. A combination of pink and white is associated with chastity and innocence, whereas a combination of pink and black links to eroticism and seduction.
Any of a group of colors reddish in hue, of medium to high lightness, and of low to moderate saturation.

The hue of that portion of the visible spectrum lying between green and indigo, evoked in the human observer by radiant energy with wavelengths of approximately 420 to 490 nanometers; any of a group of colors that may vary in lightness and saturation, whose hue is that of a clear daytime sky.

One of the three primary colors of pigments in painting and traditional color theory, as well as in the RGB color model. It lies between violet and green on the spectrum of visible light. The eye perceives blue when observing light with a dominant wavelength between approximately 450 and 495 nanometres. Most blues contain a slight mixture of other colors; azure contains some green, while ultramarine contains some violet. The clear daytime sky and the deep sea appear blue because of an optical effect known as Rayleigh scattering. An optical effect called Tyndall scattering explains blue eyes. Distant objects appear more blue because of another optical effect called aerial perspective.

Surveys in the US and Europe show that blue is the color most commonly associated with harmony, faithfulness, confidence, distance, infinity, the imagination, cold, and sometimes with sadness. In US and European public opinion polls it is the most popular color, chosen by almost half of both men and women as their favourite color. The same surveys also showed that blue was the color most associated with the masculine, just ahead of black, and was also the color most associated with intelligence, knowledge, calm and concentration.
The word "cisgender" was first published in the third edition of the Oxford English Dictionary (OED) in June 2015.
Having a gender (identity) which matches the sex one was assigned at birth; or, pertaining to such people.

A color-coded system, employed usually among the gay male casual-sex seekers or BDSM practitioners in the United States, Canada, Australia and Europe, to indicate preferred sexual fetishes, what kind of sex they are seeking, and whether they are a top/dominant or bottom/submissive. Note that, since the 1970s, many groups of LGBTQIA+ persons (not just gay men) have started using similar codes in certain spaces.
The physical or psychological fear of sexual relations or sexual intercourse.
A doctor's note issued by the governments of Imperial Germany and the Weimar Republic  under the support of sexologist Magnus Hirschfeld  identifying a person as a transvestite.
Note that, transvestite at this time referred to all individuals whose gender identity and preferred clothing did not to their assigned sex, including crossdressing and transgender people.

A syndrome characterized by chronic kidney failure and gonadal dysgenesis in phenotypic females with karyotype of 46,XY or female individual with a normal 46,XX karyotype. It is caused by donor splice-site mutations of Wilms tumor suppressor gene on chromosome 11.
Sociality and/or socialization which is not sexual or romantic in nature, as practiced between those of the same sex or gender.
The legal act by a person of adopting a new name different from their name at birth, marriage or adoption.

A person who is considered a eunuch who has not undergone castration, for any of various reasons.
